x4freetext: Structure of unbound states in Si-29 from neutron
resonance spectroscopy of Si-28 + n
Geel 150 MeV Electron Linac and the
high resolution neutron time-of-flight facility.
Pulsed beams with burst widths between 0.7 and 5 ns
at a repetition rate of 800 Hz were used.
.White neutron source with mercury-cooled uranium
target.
.Beryllium-canned water moderators were used for the
capture measurements between 1 keV and 5 MeV.
.White neutron spectrum.
.A 2 cm thick uranium filter was used in the total
cross section measurements to reduce the gamma-
flash.
.A combination of uranium, lead and B4C filters was
used in the capture measurements to reduce the
gamma-flash and to prevent overlap of low energy
neutrons.
.A metallic silicon sample of natural composition
with a thickness of 0.07356 atoms/b was used for
the transmission measurements.
.Cylindrical samples of the same composition with
8 cm diameter by 8 mm /0.04 nuclei/b/ or 16 mm
/0.07 nuclei/b/ thick, were used for the capture
measurements.
.Flight path of 400 m used for total cross section
transmission measurements.
.Flight path of 130 m used for capture measurements.
Two NE-110 scintillation detectors were used
for total cross section measurements, one of the
size 15 by 15 by 2 cm having a timing resolution of
1 ns, and the other 5 cm diameter by 2.5 cm thick
with a time resolution of 0.26 ns.
.Four 7.5 cm diameter by 7.5 cm thick bismuth-
germanate detectors, placed at 39, 90, 125 and 141
degrees with respect to the neutron beam direction,
were used for capture gamma-ray measurements.
An U-235 fission chamber placed at 30 m from
the target, was used for measuring the neutron flux
shape.
.The total cross section data were analysed with the
multi-channel multi-level R-matrix code MULTI.
.The capture data were analysed with the area code
TACASI.
.The angular distributions of the capture gamma-rays
were used for spin and parity assignments.
.The total cross section data were corrected for
dead-time and background in the TOF spectra. The
ratio background to signal was typically less than
0.1% in the region of 2 MeV, increasing to a value
of 2% at 19 MeV and 10% at 250 keV.
.The capture data were corrected for the scattered
neutron background and the Compton contribution
from higher energy gamma-rays.
.Resonance data were corrected for multiple scatter-
ing and self-shielding.
.Data taken from the references given.
